an Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the three places called Harrington (Cumberland, Lincolnshire, Northamptonshire). The Cumberland placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hæfer</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Lincolnshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hearra</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Northamptonshire derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hǣthhere</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Herendeen  .","Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hArrachtáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Arrachtán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>arrachtach</i> ‘mighty, powerful’.","Irish: in Kerry, this name was adopted as an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hIongardail</b>, later <b>Ó hUrdáil</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Iongardal</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Herington","meanings":["English: variant of   Harrington   or   Herrington  ."]},{"name":"Herrington","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Heronden in Tenterden (Kent) or Herrington in Houghton (Durham). The Kent placename may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Hȳra</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>denn</i> ‘pasture’, while the Durham placename may come from Old English <i>hæring</i> ‘rocky place’ (from <i>hær</i> ‘rock, heap of stones’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-ing</i>) or <i>hæren</i> ‘rocky’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","variant of   Harrington  ."]},{"name":"Herendeen","meanings":["Altered form of English   Harrington  ."]},{"name":"Arrington","meanings":["English:","variant of   Harrington   with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","possibly a habitational name from Arrington, a place in Cambridgeshire, named from an Old English byname, <i>Earn(a)</i>, meaning ‘eagle’ + <i>-inga-</i> ‘people or followers of’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert De Harrington V was born in 1390, in Fleet, Lincolnshire, England, his father, John de Harington, Knight of Exton, was 30 and his mother, Agnes Fleet, was 34. He had at least 3 sons with Beatric De Launde. He died in 1419, in Exton, Rutland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1390–1419":"1390–1419","1380–1428":"1380–1428","1408–Male":"1408–Surnud","1402–1485":"1402–1485","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1408–1438":"1408–1438","1420–1487":"1420–1487","1447–Male":"1447–Surnud","1360–1421":"1360–1421","1356–1421":"1356–1421","1374":"1374","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1447":"1447","1402":"1402","1356":"1356","1400":"1400","1421":"1421","1487":"1487","1420":"1420","1485":"1485","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","1428":"1428","1438":"1438","Exton, , Rutlandshire, England":"Exton, Rutland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Exton, Rutland, England, United Kingdom":"Exton, Rutland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Marbleth